s not spoil anything, but complicates the win a bit. } { [%clk 0:02:07] } (53. Rc4! { was winning easily, putting black into zugzwang. I saw the move, but not the zugzwang. I am analysing this in detail in the notes to white's 56th move, so you have some motivation to proceed further! }) 53... Rf6 { [%clk 0:01:12] } (53... Re2 54. f4+ Kg6 55. Kxb6 Re3 56. Rh3 h4 57. Rxh4 Rxg3 58. Kc5 Rg4 59. Rxg4+ fxg4 60. Kd4 g3 61. Ke3 $18) 54. Rf4 { [%clk 0:01:17] } (54. f4+? { does not work here: } 54... Kh6 55. Rh1 Rg6! 56. Rg1 (56. Rh3 Re6) 56... h4 57. Rh1 Rxg3 58. Rxh4+ Kg6 59. Rh1 Rf3 60. Rh4 Rg3 61. Kxb6 Rg4 { and black holds. }) 54... Rh6! { [%clk 0:01:06] } (54... Re6?! 55. Rc4! { leaves black in a zugzwang, as we are going to see soon. }) 55. Rc4 { [%clk 0:01:13] } 55... Re6 { White wins easily if he passes the move to black. But such things are hard to figure out with 1 minute left. } { [%clk 0:00:57] } 56. Rc6? { This move drops away the win, as black's rook is well placed. } { [%clk 0:01:12] } (56. Kb7 Rd6 { If the rook enters f6, g6 or h6 here or on the coming moves, white wins through Rc6, keeping black's rook passive and slowing down the counterplay. } 57. Ka6 Re6 58. Ka7 Rd6 59. Kb7 Re6 (59... Rf6 60. Rc6! Rf8 61. Kxb6 f4 62. Rc3 $18) 60. Kc7 $22 { Zugzwang. Black has to deteriorate his position, after which Rc6 or Kxb6 (when possible) wins easily. } 60... Rf6 (60... Kf6 61. Rc6 $18) (60... Re2 61. Kxb6 Rxf2 62. Kc5! { White's rook is ideally placed on the 4th rank, preventing black's king from advancing and being ready to enter b4 in some lines. } 62... Rf3 (62... f4 63. Rxf4 Rxf4 64. gxf4+ Kxf4 65. b6 h4 66. b7 $18) 63. b6 Rxg3 64. b7 Rb3 65. Rb4! { Here it becomes apparent why 62.Kc5! was the right move. The pawn queens. }) (60... Re4 61. Rxe4 fxe4 62. Kxb6 Kg4 63. Kc5 Kf3 64. Kd4!? Kxf2 65. Kxe4 $18) 61. Rc6 Rf8 62. Kxb6 f4 63. Rc3 $18) 56... Re2! { [%clk 0:00:56] } 57. f4+ { [%clk 0:01:11] } 57... Kg4 { [%clk 0:00:54] } 58. Rg6+ { [%clk 0:01:11] } 58... Kf3 