{ This game was played in November 2023 and has therefore no connection with the statistics. It comes from the only Titled Tuesday where I earned a prize. (I finished 4th with 9/11, earning $200.) I only mention it here as the Kramnik variation of the Queen's Indian Defense was played, at least according to the local classification. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 Bb4 8. Nbd2 d5 9. Ne5 Nbd7 10. a3 Bd6 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nc4 Be7 14. Ne5 Qe6 15. b4 c5 (15... a5! 16. b5 Ne4 $13) 16. bxc5 bxc5 17. Rb1 Rab8 18. Bf4 Bd6 19. Nd3 cxd4 20. Qa4 Bxf4 21. Nxf4 Qd6? (21... Qa6 22. Qxd4 Qxa3 23. Ra1 Qd6 24. Rxa7 { was only marginally better for white, but unwinnable for black, who has a weak d5-pawn and no counterplay. }) 22. Qxa7 Bc6 23. Rxb8 Rxb8 24. Rc1 g5 25. Nd3 (25. Rxc6? Rb1+!) 25... Bb5 { [%cal Ga7d4] } 26. Rb1! (26. Qxd4 Bxd3 (26... Qxa3? 27. Qxf6! Bxd3 28. Rc7 Bg6 29. Bxd5 $18) 27. Qxd3 $16) 26... Rb6 27. Qa5! (27. Ne5! Qxe5 28. Qxb6 Bxe2 29. Qb8+ Qxb8 30. Rxb8+ Kg7 31. Bf1! $18) 27... Qc6 28. a4 $18 Qc2 29. Rxb5 Rxb5 30. Qxb5 Qxe2 31. Bf1 Qa2 32. Qb8+ Kg7 33. Qe5 h6 34. Qxd4 { 1-0 White wins. } { A good win against a strong opponent. I play this line with both colours. It was not Pranav's best game. While my play was strong, the good moves were not too difficult to find. The moves 26.Rb1! and 27.Qa5! were not too difficult to calculate and white also had promising alternatives to them. } 1-0


